english:
  title: On a Painting of Wind and Rain
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The dark gate seals tight, sorrow-clouds turn black,
    Bright day suddenly shifts to twilight's grip.
    Heaven and earth breathe open, breathe shut—
    Mountains tremble, seas reverse; north and south confuse.

    Mad wind and violent rain rake across the earth,
    Long forests quiver, frightened by the thunder's roar.
    Small voices whisper through ten thousand hollows,
    Great voices rage—all the mountains seem to crumble.

    In such a moment, nowhere remains level ground;
    Boats tossed on waves inspire even deeper dread.
    Who is that one closing his umbrella on the cliff's edge?
    Yet in the house below, the sage sleeps soundly on.

    The painter sought to capture what cannot be bound,
    Where safety and ruin depend on each step's throw.
    All humanity dances within the archer's range—
    How laughable! The Maker's game, no more than child's play.
  footnotes:
    - 구중 (literally 'the distance of an arrow's flight') is used metaphorically to suggest human vulnerability, as if all people are within the reach of fate's arrows.
    - The sleeping sage indoors contrasts with those struggling outdoors, suggesting philosophical detachment or acceptance of nature's forces.
    - The final image of the Creator as a child playing emphasizes the insignificance of human concerns against cosmic forces.
